ce:section.ce:para:
The SiEuNPs-based ratiometric fluorescence TC assay was realized under the optimized conditions described above. As can be seen from Fig. 4
                        A–as the TC concentration increased from 0 to 10 μM, the fluorescence emission of SiEuNPs at 465 nm gradually decreased due to IFE, while the fluorescence emission at 621 nm gradually increased due to AE. Fig. 4B showed that the fluorescence intensity ratio Fr/Fb of probe had a good linear relationship with TC concentration in the range of 0.2–10 μM (R2 = 0.997), and the linear regression equation was: Fr/Fb = 0.09925c + 0.04425. The TC's limit of detection (LOD) was calculated to be 10.7 nM based on the 3σ/k principle (where σ was the standard deviation of 11 parallel measurements of blank samples, and k was the slope of the regression equation), and the detection time was only 1 min. Compared with the single-signal and dual-signal fluorescence response reported in the literature (Table 1
                        ), we can conclude that this method's detection range was within an acceptable range, which was suitable for the detection of TC. Furthermore, this method manifested significant advantages of faster response speed and higher sensitivity. In addition, a distinct color transition was observed under ultraviolet lamps (insert image in Fig. 4B). With the increase of TC concentration, the color of SiEuNPs converted from blue to red, which was further verified by CIE chromaticity diagram (Fig. 4C). The CIE coordinates of SiEuNPs gradually moved from blue (0.1676, 0.2143) to red (0.2780, 0.2399) with TC addition, which proved this chromaticity conversion could be captured by the naked eyes and provided the possibility for the visual detection of TC.
